Album Selection of 2020 | December

Already appeared with: Tears of Messiah (2017)

Concerto Moon is one of the most renowned metal bands in Japan, despite their several member changes and their link with a older era of the genre. In their fifteenth album, the fourth work since Watashi Haga joined the band, the band shows that they didn’t lose their fiery energy, bringing a powerful and compelling sound, driven by animated vocals and notable guitar riffs. Concerto Moon is definitely something Japan should be proud of.

At just 20 years old, the pop singer Junna has already shown of possess an incredible talent and much charisma, a rare thing for Japanese female voices. Debuted in the idol band Walküre, she went beyond her limits, delivering a series of releases, one better than the other. Her second album fortifies her style, in a mix of pop-rock, dance, electronic and ballad, where Junna’s living and fierce vocals always stand up in each theme featured. Junna has all the skills for becoming even more relevant in the scene and deserves to be more recognized.

Well, Sugizo doesn’t need to be introduced, but his work is always well appreciated and enjoyed, since it embraces each possible musical horizon. In his latest album he brings his own inspiration and creativity within ten different tracks, going from sumptuous and ethereal instrumental compositions to several duets with other Japanese musicians, giving a vast choice of talents to look into. Sugizo manages once again to communicate unique emotions with his music, reflecting also the hard times we’re living into.

His latest album, released for celebrating his 30th anniversary, features a cheerful and nice pop sound, mixing catchy rhythms to more passionate ones and accompained by Masaharu’s skilled vocals, making his popularity in Japan quite justified.

This thing hasn’t changed with the twelfth album, which features an energetic and various sound, including catchy melodies, aggressive notes and charismatic vocals. Angelo may appear to be formulaic, but if their style works and always delivers, why not give it a chance?

An album made for everyone, for who has the heart and the soul for enjoying a timeless music, going beyond time and space.

Sokoninaru can be definitely considered one of the last revelations of Japanese music. Formed on 2011, this duo has a really unique style compared to other rock bands, with a sound embracing shades of progressive and hard rock. Their latest work focuses mainly on the intensity brought by their sound, where the guitars create an incredible effect, between hard hits and piercing riffs, along with paced rhythms and quite mature vocals, shaping up each song in an unique way. Sokoninaru can definitely boost the Japanese rock scene.

In their latest work, their sound maintains the gritty and enigmatic vibe which always characterized them, but there’s also a pleasant electronic vibe, distributed on each track according to the style, driven by Atsushi Sakurai’s sumptuous vocals and a really refined instrumental work. If you are looking for something different, but also belonging to Buck-Tick, this album is definitely your choice.

Their latest EP sees a really enigmatic sound, with shaded notes, electronic vibes and a cohesive rhythm, creating an unique atmosphere, driven by an awesome vocal work by the singers Yusei Tsuruta and Eriko Takano. Here I am with a new review in “Throwback Thursday”! Today’s subject is the debut release by the visual kei band Bless This Mess, the mini-album Hymn, released on 24th January 2016. If you don’t know them, they formed on 2015 and led by YNG (vo.), former guitarist of Saruin and vocalist of Jabell, who has been accompained at that time by Ranmaru (gt.), former member of Para:noir, and Baku (ba.), another member of Saruin and Jabell. And now... let’s review!

-Hymn: the title-track opens the mini-album, a short intro filled by a dark atmosphere and slow notes, accompained by a melancholic piano.

-Kakushoku (Erosion): the song starts with a fast drumming, accompaining deep vocals, leading up to a strong and structured theme, well built by the instruments; YNG’s piercing vocals drive up the song, made by an aggressive and dark melody. ---> 9/10

-Barbarism: this song sees a faster rhythm, with powerful guitar lines bringing more energy into the melody; YNG’s voice is obscure and rapid, fitting in the theme quite easily; another strong song, maintaining high the level of the release. ---> 9/10

-16: deep notes and a steady drumming characterize the song, with darker and extreme vocals which dictate the whole thing’s atmosphere; the theme results being heavier than expected, even thanks to the compelling guitar work. ---> 9/10

-Slumber: the mini-album ends with a song opened by softer and melancholic notes, with YNG’s vibrant and deep vocals accompained by idyllic notes, making his interpretation more suggestive; the theme goes on with a really good rhythm, well articulated by the single instruments, building up an unique ballad, which reaches its own peak with a fantastic guitar solo. ---> 10/10

Final Vote ---> 9/10

Bless This Mess belongs to the wide group of visual kei bands which didn’t have the luck to see their talent recognized at all. This mini-album is surely their best work to date, bringing in an heavy and enigmatic metal sound, accompained by energy and melancholy, all enclosed in a contained and solid product, where YNG’s voice is the best highlight. The band had experienced a change of line-up in 2017, when the historical members Ranmaru and Baku left the band, substituted by Jin Tateishi, former guitarist of Ansia, and Rega, bassist of Srash Notes Garden, leading the band to be signed under Starwave Records, a label which would have brought them more popularity, even thanks to the pretty good album Xiall Rain. On 2018 the band gained an official drummer, Hakuya, of NightingeiL fame, and released their first and unfortunately only EP Blind Circus, before their disbandment, occurred at the end of that year. Despite their short and unlucky path, Bless This Mess is a band everyone should listen to, since the sound they had is quite rare, especially in the current scene. A mini-album for who had followed Bless This Mess’ short career or needs to get into a compelling and not so known band.

Here I am with a new special in “Focusing on”! Today’s subject is a Japanese rock band, whose style is disruptive and hard to miss. We’re talking about Breakerz, formed on 2007 and composed by Daigo Naitou (vo.), already famous for his solo project Daigo☆Stardust, Akihide Satou (gt.), who is recognized for his solo works and for the short-lived project Never Land, and Shinpei Inoue (gt.). The band name comes from their own concept, based on breaking all the possible musical schemes in order to bring new and energetic music. Their genre is a fusion between English rock music, provided by Akihide, and American style, brought by Shinpei, accompained by Daigo’s sensual voice. Their debut occurred on July 2007 with the first album Breakerz.

One of the lead-tracks, named Wake up my soul, sees a strong and rebel rock sound, well characterized by each member’s work; the song is about the importance of ties in a changing world. It has been followed by the second album Crash & Build, the first mini-album Ao no mirai (Pale future) and the singles Summer Party/Last Emotion and Sekai wa odoru/Shakunetsu (Dancing world/Hot).

The first lead-track has an heartfelt rock melody, kept up by a vibrating rhythm and nice vocals; the song is about the importance of ties in an ever-changing world. It has been followed by the single Angelic Smile/Winter Party, the third album Big Bang! and the singles Grand Finale, Everlasting Luv/Bambino, Hikari (Light) and Love Fighter -Koi no Battle-, the fourth album Fighterz, the acoustic mini-album B.R.Z. Acoustic and the single Gekijou (Passion)/Heaven.

The first title-track is a pretty animated rock track, with a fluid rhythm and a catchy melody, hard to forget; the song is about the feelings, so powerful to make someone losing his mind. It has been followed by the singles Bunny Love, Tsukiyo no itazura no maho (Magical trick of night light)/Climber x Climber and Last † Pray/Zettai! I love you (I absolutely love you!), the fifth album Go, the singles Miss Mystery and Overwriting/Nounai Survivor (Survivor in the brain), the compilation Breakerz Best -Single Collection- and the single Rusty Hearts.

The title-track sees a faster and more energetic rock sound, with relevant dark and gothic shades; the song is about fighting until the end for the loved one. It has been followed by the single We Go, the sixth album 0 -Zero- and the single Yaiba (Sword). The band came back with new releases after two years, starting with the single Ikusen no meikyuu de ikusen no nazo wo doite (Solve thousand of mysteries in thousand of labyrinths), followed by another single, Yume monogatari (Dream story), the seventh album X, the singles DxDxD/Great Ambitious -Single version-, Atarashii sekai he atarashii jidai he -Reiwa version- (In a new world, in a new era), Yamiyo ni mau aoi tori (Blue bird dancing in the dark night), the compilation Breakerz x Detective Conan Collaboration Best and the single Barabara (Scattered)/Love Stage.

Since 2007 Breakerz has always distinguished for their fresh and engaging sound, allowing them to deliver good and flowing tracks without any effort. The rocking trio composed by Daigo, Shinpei and Akihide manage to combine several elements in each song, bringing their energy into each note and having fun with the most unexpected shades. Their style allowed them to be more popular, especially among anime fans, since they provided several themes for the famous anime Detective Conan, appeared as guests in several tribute albums, such as Tribute of Mucc -En- and Hide Tribute Impulse and are planning to release a new single, I Love my Daughter, on February 2021. But we shouldn’t forget about the activities of the single members, which are still active and prolific; Daigo released a bunch of singles between 2013 and 2018, Akihide recently brought out his eighth album Loop World, and Shinpei did a solo live project in 2019. So Breakerz is one of the band which is hard to miss within the scene, especially if you like energetic melodies.

Who might enjoy: who loves energetic melodies and wants to be always surprised.

Recommended songs: Wake up my soul, Sekai wa odoru, Everlasting Luv, Gekijou, Last † Pray, Rusty Hearts and Barabara.
